# Quality Standards

## Definition of Ready (DoR)

A spec must meet ALL of these before implementation starts (`/plan` produces them):

- [ ] Goal is clear: who / what / why
- [ ] Acceptance criteria are **observable** and testable (no vague "should work well")
- [ ] Approach + key interfaces are sketched
- [ ] Subtasks are defined and independently committable
- [ ] No open questions remain

## Definition of Done (DoD)

A feature is done only when ALL of these are true:

- [ ] Full gate green (`ci.sh full` — format, lint, typecheck, all tests, build)
- [ ] `/verify` passed (gate + review + manual smoke for new features); smoke-found bugs became automated tests
- [ ] Review addressed (inline self-review, or the `reviewer` agent for critical diffs)
- [ ] Documentation updated where the change warrants (architecture.md, user docs if user-facing)
- [ ] Merged to the integration branch (local git, or `/pr` if used)
- [ ] Spec moved to `docs/specs/completed/`

## Quality Gates

| Gate | Trigger | Owner |
|------|---------|-------|
| Auto-format | Every file edit | Hook (PostToolUse) |
| Fast gate (`ci.sh fast`) | Per subtask | `runner` (Haiku), local |
| Full gate (`ci.sh full`) + smoke | Feature-done (`/verify`) | `runner` + `smoke-tester`, local |
| Review | Critical diffs only | inline self-review, or the `reviewer` agent (best/high) |
| GitHub Actions CI | Human commits + releases only | GitHub Actions |
| Documentation | Inline during `/implement` (minimal) | main session |

## Test Strategy

**Configured scope:** {{TESTING_SCOPE}}. Test the **important behaviors** — quality over coverage. Each acceptance criterion maps to the lowest test level that meaningfully covers it.

- **Unit** — isolated logic (pure functions, domain rules, validation, calculations). Mock only external I/O (network, FS, DB, time); never mock your own code. Error cases and boundaries live here.
- **Integration** *(from "Unit + Integration")* — system boundaries (HTTP endpoints, DB operations, service interactions) against real test dependencies (test DB / in-memory), no mocks of your own layers. Don't repeat what unit tests cover.
- **E2E** *(only at "Unit + Integration + E2E")* — critical user flows spanning UI + backend + DB that aren't verifiable at integration level. Cap ~3–5 scenarios per feature; only when an E2E framework is actually configured.

Glue code (thin controllers, adapters, wrappers) is covered indirectly by integration tests — no dedicated unit tests needed.

## Security
- Security is reviewed as part of `/verify` (self-review, or the `reviewer` agent for auth/crypto/payments/data diffs).
- Dependency audits run in the canonical gate / CI.
- No secrets in code — use environment variables; `.env` is protected by the file-protection hook.
